<s1 id=SelectPaletteTA> To Select a Palette
 
        <idx|palette: selecting|
        <idx|changing: colors|
        <idx|color: changing|
        <idx|workspace: colors, changing|
        <idx|selecting: palette|
        <idx|dialog box: Color|
        <idx|Color dialog box|
 
<list order>
 
* Click the Style Manager Color control.
 
* Select a palette from the Palettes list.
 
* Click OK.
 
<\list>
 
Desktop colors come from predefined color palettes.  The 
Color dialog box lists the palettes that
came with your system plus any palettes you have added.
 
<!-- <figure nonumber entity=ColorDialogBox>
<\figure>
 
<list plain tight>
 
* ((1)) List of palettes.
 
* ((2)) Color buttons, representing the selected palette's colors.
 
<\list>  -->
 
For a description of the dialog box controls,
see <xref SMColorDialogDE>.
 
<procedure> See Also
 
<list bullet tight>
 
* <xref ModifyPaletteTA>
 
* <xref CreatePaletteTA>
 
<\list>
 
 
<s1 id=ModifyPaletteTA> To Modify a Palette
 
        <idx|palette: modifying|
        <idx|modifying: palette|
        <idx|modifying: colors|
 
<note>
This procedure changes the color settings of the currently selected
palette.  If you have a default palette (one of the palettes provided
with the Desktop) selected, you may want to copy it. 
(See <xref CreatePaletteTA>.)
This ensures that you can return to the original
settings of the default palette if necessary.
<\note>
 
<list order>
* Click the Style Manager Color control.
 
* Select a palette in the Color dialog box.
 
* Double-click a color button to open the Modify Color dialog box.  <newline>
  !!Or!!, click a color button, then click Modify.
 
* Adjust the settings in the Modify Color dialog box.
 
* Click OK in the Modify Color dialog box.
 
* Repeat steps 2-4 to modify another color button.
 
* Click OK in the Color dialog box.
 
<\list>
 
        <idx|Color dialog box|
        <idx|dialog box: Color|
        <idx|Modify Color dialog box|
        <idx|dialog box: Modify Color|
        <idx|colors: changing palette|
        <idx|palette: changing colors|
 
<!-- <figure nonumber entity=ModifyDialogBox>
<\figure>
 
<list plain tight>
 
* ((1)) Shows the current color.
 
* ((2)) Shows the new color as you make changes.
 
* ((3)) Displays a pointer for you to choose a color in the workspace.
 
* ((4)) Changes red, green, and blue values.
 
* ((5)) Changes red, green, and blue proportions.
 
* ((6)) Changes the color's purity.
 
* ((7)) Changes the color's brightness.
 
<\list>  -->
 
 
<procedure>To Grab a Color from the Workspace
 
        <idx|grabbing: color from workspace|
        <idx|color: grabbing from workspace|
 
<list order>
 
* Click Grab Color.
  The grab pointer appears.
 
* Move the pointer to an area of color on the workspace that you want
  to grab.
 
* Click OK to make that color the New color.
 
<\list>
 
For a description of the Modify Color dialog box controls,
see <xref SMModifyPaletteDialogDE>.
 
<procedure> See Also
 
<list bullet tight>
 
* <xref CreatePaletteTA>
 
<\list>
 
 
<s1 id=CreatePaletteTA> To Create a Custom Palette

        <idx|palette: adding|
        <idx|palette: creating|
        <idx|palette: copying|
        <idx|creating: custom palette|
        <idx|copying: palette, copying|
        <idx|Color dialog box|
        <idx|dialog box: Color|
 
<list order>
 
* Click the Style Manager Color control.

* Choose Add in the Color dialog box.
 
* Type the new palette in the New Palette field.
 
* Click OK in the Add Palette dialog box.
 
* Click Modify and modify the palette (See <xref ModifyPaletteTA>.)
 
* Click OK in the Color dialog box.
 
<\list>
 
Adding a palette makes a copy of the currently selected palette and gives the
copy a unique name.   You then modify
the copy, keeping the original palette intact.
 
 
<procedure> See Also
 
<list bullet tight>
 
* <xref ModifyPaletteTA>
 
<\list>
 
 
<s1 id=DeletePaletteTA> To Delete a Palette
 
        <idx|palette: deleting|
        <idx|dialog box: Delete Palette|
        <idx|deleting: palette|
 
<list order>
 
* Click the Style Manager Color control.

* Select the palette from the Palettes list.
 
* Choose Delete.
 
* Click OK in the Delete Palette dialog box to confirm deletion.
 
<\list>
 
 
<procedure>To Restore a Deleted Palette
 
        <idx|palette: restoring deleted|
        <idx|restoring: deleted palette|
 
<list order>
 
* Open a File Manager view of the showing %%HomeDirectory%%/.dt/palettes folder.
 
* For system palettes, remove the file ~%%PaletteName%%.``dp''.
 
* For user added palettes, rename the deleted palette
  from ~%%PaletteName%%.``dp'' to %%PaletteName%%.``dp''.
 
* Restart Style Manager (close, then reopen).
 
<\list>
 
When you delete a palette, Style Manager places a copy of the palette
in the .dt/palettes subfolder in your home folder.  The file name
of this copy begins with ``~''.
 
 
<procedure> See Also
 
<list bullet tight>
 
* <link hyperlink="Filemgr ToRenameAnObjectTA" type=JumpNewView> To rename
  a file or folder<\link>.
 
<\list>
 
 
<s1 id=LimitColorUseTA> To Change the Number of Colors Used by the Desktop
 
        <idx|color: limiting usage|
        <idx|limiting: color usage|
        <idx|changing: number of colors|
 
<list order>
* Click the Style Manager Color control.
 
* Choose Number of Colors in the Color dialog box.
 
* Select a color use option to set the number of colors used in the
  desktop.  (See <xref SMColorConcepts> for information on how the desktop
  uses colors.)
 
* Click OK in the Number of Colors dialog box.
 
* Click OK in the Color dialog box.
 
<\list>
 
You must log out and log back in before this change takes effect.
 
        <idx|Color dialog box|
        <idx|dialog box: Color|
 
<!-- <figure nonumber entity=ColorUseDialogBox>
<\figure> -->
 
